Task 1 - House Price Prediction¶

Submitted by - Shivank Udayawal¶

Problem Statement :¶

  • Predicting the Boston Housing Price.

About Dataset :¶

  • The Boston Housing Dataset is a derived from information collected by the U.S. Census Service concerning housing in the area of Boston MA.

  • The following describes the dataset columns:

    1. CRIM - per capita crime rate by town
    2. ZN - proportion of residential land zoned for lots over 25,000 sq.ft.
    3. INDUS - proportion of non-retail business acres per town.
    4. CHAS - Charles River dummy variable (1 if tract bounds river; 0 otherwise)
    5. NOX - nitric oxides concentration (parts per 10 million)
    6. RM - average number of rooms per dwelling
    7. AGE - proportion of owner-occupied units built prior to 1940
    8. DIS - weighted distances to five Boston employment centres
    9. RAD - index of accessibility to radial highways

    10. TAX - full-value property-tax rate per $10,000

    11. PTRATIO - pupil-teacher ratio by town

    12. B - 1000(Bk - 0.63)^2 where Bk is the proportion of blacks by town
    13. LSTAT - % lower status of the population
    14. MEDV - Median value of owner-occupied homes in $1000's

for k, v in Data_boston.items():
        q1 = v.quantile(0.25)
        q3 = v.quantile(0.75)
        irq = q3 - q1
        v_col = v[(v <= q1 - 1.5 * irq) | (v >= q3 + 1.5 * irq)]
        perc = np.shape(v_col)[0] * 100.0 / np.shape(Data_boston)[0]
        print("Column %s outliers = %.2f%%" % (k, perc))

In [30]:
from sklearn import metrics
y_train_predict = lin_model.predict(X_train)
rmse = (np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(Y_train, y_train_predict)))
r2 = r2_score(Y_train, y_train_predict)

print("\n")
print("The model performance for Training Set")
print('Mean Square Error (MSE)       :', metrics.mean_squared_error(Y_train,y_train_predict))

print('R2 score is                   :', r2_score(Y_train, y_train_predict))

print('Root mean Square Error (RMSE) :', np.sqrt(metrics.mean_squared_error(Y_test,y_test_predict)))
print('R2 score is                   :', r2_score(Y_test, y_test_predict))
